Camille Auer wanted to correct her gender, was diagnosed with mental illness and now she makes art on the subject - "Man should have a right to his own body"
Dozens of patient records hang from the roof of the Project room gallery of the Academy of Fine Arts.
Each of them says Camille Auer's name.
The papers tell a multi-year story of how outside people have written down their interpretation of Auer and his identity.
Decided for him who he is.
"I wanted to tell you my personal treatment history so that the violence in the process would become visible," Auer says.
By the process, he refers to the sex correction process.
It is often a years-long research period that includes meetings with psychologists, psychiatrists, nurses, and doctors.
The process begins with a referral to diagnosis studies of "gender identity disorder", which are conducted in Tampere and Helsinki.
For Auer, the process started four years ago.
Even before this, he had used the estrogen he had ordered over the internet and was well advanced in his own repair process.
She felt she was a woman, but according to Finnish law, a person must go through the correction process in order to also legally correct the gender.
The Translaki, or Act on Strengthening the Gender of Transsec Sual (563/2002), obliges transgender people to forced sterilization in order to bring the right gender to a population register centre and passport, for example.
Currently, every person who corrects their gender is required to have a psychiatric diagnosis and a certificate of reproductive incapacity.
It is up to a person to have the right to decide their own body.
"This situation is intolerable and violates human rights," says Auer.
Translain reform has been talked about in Finland for a long time.
The UN Human Rights Council has made eight comments on the law and the European Court of Justice has a preliminary decision obliging the parties to the European Convention on Human Rights to respect self-determination.
The previous Finnish government prepared a change in the law under the leadership of then Minister of Social Affairs and Health Susanne Huovinen.
Elections came and the Finns Party rose to the government.
Now the bill is stuck again.
It is a domestic policy dispute that is not even related to this law.
"The government does not want to put it on the table because there are disagreements within the government about the amendment of the law," says Frank Johansson, Executive Director of Amnesty International's Finnish branch.
The front of the exhibition space is dominated by two large installations.
One of them consists of the packaging and instructions for use of the drugs used by Auer.
In the Patient Report installation, any visitor can read, for example, the interpretation of Auer by the psychologist of the Tampere University Hospital's transpolice.
The psychologist met Camille Auer twice and wrote a story based on these that would define Auer's right to care and help.
The sense of reality being studied appears exposed to vacillation.
The subject's perception of self appears to be fragmented in a borderline way and the unstable traits associated with personality are emphasized.
Auer did not recognize himself from these descriptions.
"It was a shock to hear that I was diagnosed with mental illness," Auer says.
An even greater shock was when Auer was not granted sex reassignment treatment.
According to the medical staff, his resources were not sufficient to start the process.
He was denied his own identity.
Then, on February 11, 2015, Auer walked out of the meeting and kicked the television in the waiting hall of the transponder.
Later, a work of art called Monument for the Excluded was born on that television, in which Auer reflected his experience of power and its use.
"It's crazy that anyone who's defined as a woman at birth can enlarge their breasts, but you need a diagnosis to remove your breasts," Auer says.
Your body is not yours if you feel you are anything other than the amount of gender you have defined at birth.
Unfortunately, Auer's experience is not the only one of its kind.
The sex correction process is harder for many for mental reasons than for purely medical operations.
Those who go through it meet dozens of people who need to be justified by their own existence and right to their own sex experience.
"It's crazy that people who need support and help are denied treatment, citing that their resources are not enough," Auer says.
Many people who seek the process have psychological symptoms behind them: depression, anxiety, possible bullying experiences.
On the basis of these, medical staff may order that treatment cannot be started.
"Preventing treatment and getting help can plunge a person into an even worse situation than it was before the process began," Auer says.
Auer's personal exhibition also deals with anxiety and thoughts about suicide.
In the text of the exhibition publication, Auer writes: "I have had suicidal thoughts throughout my adult life and that is something that people usually find difficult to digest".
Depression has been treated with drugs and when Auer started using hormones, it became easier.
He had finally been able to say the feelings that had existed since childhood and teens.
Why the wide chin didn't seem to fit your body and why the chest muscles had to be round instead of flat chest.
The most important thing for Auer has been that there are people around him who see him.
Being seen is a basic need.
"You have to justify yourself so much by talking, dressing, using sound and moving," he says.
Today, Auer feels he is already seen, he exists as a woman.
However, in the early stages of the process, the random comments of loved ones could hurt a lot.
What hurts the most is when people close to you misgender.
"They should know and they know who I am but they won't or won't be able to internalize it," he continues.
Not all trans people need physical changes.
They do not suffer from body dysphoria, or body conflict, where the body or parts of it can cause anxiety and even physical pain.
However, without the use of hormones and the long research process, one cannot get official confirmation of one's gender.
"There is no medical basis for these studies," Auer says.
And that's true.
In Denmark, for example, in June 2014, Parliament approved a new procedure for recognising the legal sex.
The new legislation is based on self-determination in terms of legal gender.
The adult applicant makes a written application for a new personal identity code, telling them that he or she feels of another gender.
After a six-month period of reflection, the applicant confirms his application in writing and the Ministry issues the applicant with a new personal identity code.
This right to self-determination is also required in Finland and this requirement is also crystallized by Auer's exhibition.
It has not been a therapy experience for the artist, but an exhibition is a political and artistic collection of works.
I want to believe that art still has weight and that it can bring about political changes at a time when politicians have forgotten human rights.
