NGO issues travel warning to Missouri
The National NAACP, which promotes African American civil rights, has issued a travel warning for Missouri, due to state discriminatory practices and racist attacks there.
"NAACP's travel bulletin for Missouri will come into effect on August 28, 2017, calling on African-American tourists, visitors and locals to pay special attention and exercise extreme caution when traveling in a state that has recently had numerous questionable racial events," the organization said in a statement.
The law, which recently came into force in Missouri, makes it difficult to export cases of discrimination to court, and the enforcement of state laws is disproportionately directed at minorities. According to NAACP, these factors led to the issuing of a travel warning.
"People's civil rights are violated.
They are stopped by skin color and beaten or killed," NAACP Missouri Chairman Rod Chapel told Kansas City Star.
"We've never heard of so many cases in such a short time before."
The Missouri Travel Bulletin is the organization's first warning about the U.S. state.
The organization cited racist comments against African-American students at the University of Missouri and the death of 28-year-old black Tory Sanders from Tennessee as examples.
Sanders died under questionable circumstances earlier this year, and he was driving through the state when his car ran out of fuel, and he was arrested by Missouri police, even though he was not charged with a crime.
The travel bulletin also referred to the Missouri Attorney General's report that police are 75% more likely to stop a black driver than white.
"The purpose of the travel bulletin is to urge people to be on guard and warn their families, friends and colleagues about what can happen in Missouri," Chapel says.
"People need to prepare for things like involving money to pay bail or telling relatives they're going to travel through the state."
The FBI said 100 hate crimes were recorded in Missouri in 2015, the sixteenth highest in the U.S. states.
The travel warning is also a response to Missouri's new law, which makes it difficult for companies to sue for discrimination in housing and employment relationships.
ACLU recently issued travel warnings to Texas and Arizona after they passed immigration laws that oblige police to arrest people for immigration violations. According to the organization, this increases racial profiling.
Travel warnings are usually published by the State Department and apply to other states, but have recently been published by NGOs in response to certain laws and developments in the United States.
