Trump's White House now targets Statue of Liberty
Addressing the statues is the surest sign of a change of power.
Americans know that as well as anyone else: Iraqis, along with American soldiers, knocked down Saddam Hussein's statue in Firdos Square in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the Trump administration's main ideologists, knew well what he was doing in a heated debate with CNN channel Jim Acosta. The Statue of Liberty was attacked by Miller in a verbatim concerning the president's proposal to reduce legal immigration considerably.
Miller didn't really criticize the statue itself.
If he had done so, he would have been attacked by huge herds of cruise organizers and characters imitating the Statue of Liberty.
His attack was on the meaning of the statue, and especially on the addition of a poem by Emma Lazarus in 1903 — 17 years after the statue was completed.
Miller thus rayed Acosta: "I don't want to go into more detail about it now, but the Statue of Liberty is... a symbol of American freedom that illuminates the whole world.
The poem was later added and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty."
Miller was not wrong in himself, but it is not just a matter of history, as he himself said.
Essential are Lazarus' touching words, the only ones of their kind in which the state not only calls immigrants but the "poor poorest of the poor": "Your tired, your poor, / Your huddled masses year to breast free, / The wretched refuse of your doing shore."
The poem is now more relevant than ever.
Miller did not practice literary criticism, and he made it clear that the "poor poorest of the poor" are not welcome in Trump's United States.
The dispute over the importance of the Statue of Liberty is part of a broader political and cultural dispute over the importance of the United States.
Lazarus' friends campaigned after his death to attach the poem to the statue's pedestal, well knowing that the act was strongly political.
The purpose of the statue was to embody the connections between French and American republicanism with a classical symbol, the feminine embodiment of freedom.
Lazarus changed its meaning: in his poem, the female figure is no longer abstract, but has a voice.
And it gives itself a new name: the mother of the exiled.
The inclusion of the poem in the image was a brilliant feminist coup and a devastating attack on the American idea of nationality.
Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, and the right has long wanted to turn it back into the original.
Rush Limbaugh — a mouthpiece who can now be considered some sort of sign of Trump — claimed in 2010 that the Statue of Liberty does not present anyone with an invitation, but is an early pioneer of neoconservatives, taking the United States' torch into a world covered with darkness: "Lady Liberty steps forward.
He takes the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch does not lead the way to the United States."
Rarely, Limbaugh was partly right.
The importance of the Statue of Liberty depends entirely on the point of view.
Lazarus saw it as the poor and exhausted but hopeful immigrants from the deck of the ship after a long and trying journey.
He saw it from the perspective of people looking for shelter and a better life.
His Statue of Liberty comforts by giving hope and welcoming.
And that's not what Miller and Trump want under any circumstances.
Their torches do not lead the way but incite the flames of hatred, their only source of power.
