Blocking critics on Facebook: Don't run for public office if you can't stand criticism
Our country's father knew what bad publicity was.
The Americans loved George Washington, but newspapers soon began criticizing him for all possible domestic politics, all the way to his political principles.
Criticism must have irritated,
But he did not silence his critics.
"If freedom of speech is abolished, we may be led stupid and quiet like sheep to slaughter," Washington said in 1783.
That's how we get to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who should learn from Washington.
Hogan staff have removed at least 450 comments from his official Facebook page and blocked their authors.
The U.S. Civil Rights Federation sued Hogan earlier this week.
His staff found the challenge unfounded, and the attitude was also dismissive online.
"What does it matter? This is just Facebook," many commented.
But it matters,
Especially in the case of Hogan.
Hogan is the amazingly popular Republican governor of a Democratic-controlled state.
He has received the second best reviews of his operations among the 50 governors.
Hogan is not sensitive to hothead.
He has led the state firmly and has adhered strictly to the principles.
He has also used Facebook as the main channel of communication with his constituents and published a picture of his bald head in chemotherapy there.
Therefore, blocking users who come to the Governor's Facebook page is unnecessary and even dangerous. The Governor's page is a public and official forum maintained by his staff with tax money.
Hogan spokesman Amelia Chasse defended the governor's actions in an interview with the Washington Post, who said it was just a matter of moderated comments.
However, labeling commentators as trolls, spammers, or haters is too easy a solution.
The Washington Post interviewed users blocked by Hogan on Facebook.
They turned out to be ordinary people who wanted to talk to the leaders they chose, not trolls, but teachers, entrepreneurs, and pastors, for example.
They reported that their comments were respectful, thoughtful, and factual.
In his comment, the pastor quoted the Bible; he wanted to appeal to Hogan's Catholic faith.
Lawyer Lakshmi Sarma Ramani of Bowie, Maryland, was not hostile but asked the question of hate crimes.
"I politely commented that I was disappointed that Hogan had not taken a stand on hate crimes and other recent news," he wrote in comments from the Washington Post.
"I also cannot accept that when more people comment on the same thing, they are immediately considered an organized group and ignored as a large group of concerned citizens."
The governor's staff called the comments a "focused attack," and someone else might call them "promoting things that were considered important.
In Facebook's era, communication is easy to manage by blocking a reviewer or deleting a critical comment.
In the old days, staff should have been sent to collect and burn newspapers with critical editorials published, or to arrest and silence protesters.
But it is really the same thing, now only digitally.
Hogan is not the first public official to be accused of chaining Facebook and other social media channels.
Twitter users blocked by President Trump have sued him.
The first major decision was made last week in Virginia.
According to Alexandria District Court judge James C. Cacheris, the Loudoun County government violated the first amendment to the United States Constitution in blocking the voter on Facebook.
And the U.S. Civil Rights Federation went to talk to Kentucky Republican Governor Matt Bevin about Twitter and Facebook's use.
This shouldn't be hard.
In Washington, low-cost postage payments had a similar effect to the internet today.
The number of newspapers quadrupled from 1776 to 1800, and anonymous writers hammered Washington.
There were trolls at the time.
Nicknames Juricola, Valerius, Belisarius, and Portius wrote letters to the newspapers barking at Washington's decisions.
The President's office was flooded with petitions criticizing Jay's agreement, the U.S.-UK cooperation, trade and shipping agreement, as evidenced by documents collected by the Papers of George Washington network project.
However, he did not silence his critics.
Freedom of speech, freedom of opinion and freedom of conversation are the cornerstones of our nation.
True leadership means accepting this fact.
