Poverty and Death in Indonesia's Golden Land
Bardina Degei does not use stove in cooking.
Even a boiler he rarely uses.
Degei lives in a wooden building in Enarotal, the capital of the Paniai region, located in Indonesia's troubled province of Papua. When he makes dinner, he usually puts the sweet potato — locally "nota" — directly into the fireplace.
After half an hour, the sweet potato that was burned to the carrh is eaten voraciously with bare, unwashed hands.
Degei's home has no furniture, sitting on a muddy ground floor, where he usually also handles his daily chores, such as washing in cloudy water retrieved from a nearby swamp.
The toilet is delivered by a bucket in a catless room.
Degei is the youngest of her husband's four wives and has not been assigned fields to care for.
Polygamy is common here.
Working late can be dangerous: most of the men in the village are unemployed, and many drink a lot. In addition, soldiers must be taken into account.
"No one dares to walk in the village after 5 p.m.," Degei says.
This is a rare peek into everyday life in the Papua Highlands, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969. The annexation was preceded by a controversial referendum in which 1,026 village elders were forced to vote publicly in front of the occupying forces.
The local independence movement, which opposed Dutch power, quickly turned its hatred into the Jakarta government, which keeps the region under strict control and prevents foreign journalists and human rights observers from entering it.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and Western Papua, the eastern part of the island belonging to Papua New Guinea.
The enarotal is remote and bleak, and the journey there begins with a flight of one and a half hours from the provincial capital Jayapura to Nabire and continues on a five-hour roadway to the stomach with a rental car.
There's no public transport here.
The city of about 19,000 inhabitants has wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, the corrugated roofs of which have been stained into yellow browns by rust.
Few Indonesians have been here, not to mention journalists and foreigners.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, the Mee Pago tribesmen of Papua worshipped the god Uga Tamee.
Other changes have occurred.
"We didn't have clothes like this," Degei says. He means his colorful, hand-woven wraphead skirt, dark skirt, and brightly colored blouse.
"Before we had only leaves to cover our bodies."
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, with 28% of its inhabitants living below the poverty line, and infant mortality and illiteracy are among the highest in Asia.
But it is also the gold country of Indonesia.
Paniai is a highland area about the size of New Jersey with 153,000 inhabitants. Only about 100 kilometers from Pania is Grasberg, the world's largest and most lucrative gold mine, owned by Freeport McMoran, a company based in Phoenix, USA.
In 2015, the mine generated $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper for Freeport.
In addition, Papua has an estimated $78 billion in wood reserves.
However, for the Papuans, these riches bring misery, as they mean the repressive presence of an Indonesian strong army.
In 2005, the New York Times revealed that Freeport paid local military personnel and military local units nearly $20 million between 1998 and 2004. Individual officers were paid up to $150,000.
Papua's demands for greater sovereignty threaten this source of income and are mercilessly silenced.
Human rights activists say that more than 500,000 beans have been killed, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian army since 1969.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, massacres in the highlands of the Papua tribes in the 1970s took on the proportions of genocide.
Last year, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 people in the area during peaceful protests.
The Brisbane Archdiocese report We Will Lose Everything of 2016 contains stories of previous year's atrocities, such as executions without trial, torture — rapes and electric shocks are particularly popular means — and relentless attacks toward peaceful demonstrations.
"It's difficult to calculate the number of victims because there are weekly cases," says Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch.
The screws have been tightened as Papua's natural resources attract migrants from other parts of Indonesia.
Of the 3.5 million inhabitants of the province, 83% are Christians, but the demographics are changing as Indonesia's populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawes move to the region in hopes of a better livelihood for Muslims.
Javan warung food stalls sell fried chicken and gado gado vegetables in peanut sauce.
Locals find it difficult to compete.
"Changers have started selling chicken and vegetables in the market cheaper than locals," says 24-year-old Abeth You, who is from Paniai and moved to the provincial capital for work.
"Local women lost their clients."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, nicknamed Yokowi, promised in his 2014 election campaign to address Papua's injustices and human rights violations.
Papua consists of 29 regions, and this former carpenter won the vote in 27 regions, including Pania, on his way to Jakarta Presidential Palace.
But little has changed in Papua, and the locals feel betrayed.
"Our hearts were broken because we voted for Jokowi in 2014 and expected him to fulfill our wishes and restore justice," You says.
Pania experienced some kind of trough just two months after Jokowi's October inauguration.
Eleven children were singing Christmas songs by the fire in Enarotal on 7 December 2014, when two Indonesian soldiers appeared on motorcycles from the dark.
The frightened children told the soldiers they should use headlights.
One of the soldiers did not like the remark, and according to local pastor Yavedt Tebai, the man returned with four soldiers.
According to reports by victims and witnesses, drunk soldiers caught the children and assaulted them with rifles.
That's how one of the soldiers shot at the kids.
One of the children, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, fell into a coma as a result of the assault.
A couple of hours later, the building of the State Election Commission near the scene was set on fire, and the next day began to happen.
About 1,000 parrots —young men and women and children — gathered at the football field in front of a local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They had hunting springs for ceremonies with them, and they began performing the traditional waita dance of the Mee Pago tribe of Papua, where they danced in the ring and imitated bird song.
Some of the protesters began to stone police and military buildings.
When the mood got hot, the soldiers were ordered in the internal radio system: "If the crowds resist more than three times, shoot them to death." The information is based on an official document seen by TIME magazine that has not been released to local media.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, resident leader of Kego Koto, sensed the situation would get out of hand and asked the crowd to calm down and return to their homes.
No one wanted to listen anymore.
"When I turned around, I was shot on the left wrist," he told TIME magazine on the porch of his brightly colored painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn't know who shot him, but the bullet came from the soldiers' ranks.
"A number of shots were fired in Väentungos."
Alfius Youw was shot three times, and his cousin saw the shootings.
"I ran to him and made sure it was really him," Yohanes told TIME magazine sad. Like many Indonesians, he uses only one name.
"I saw that he was dead... I kissed him."
Papua Police Superintendent Yotje Mende told reporters that police only "protected" the police station because it was under attack.
"We must defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us," Papua Police spokesman Pudjo Sulistiyo said in 2015.
"That's when it's about life and death."
Human Rights Watch said five young protesters were killed and many injured.
The news of the killings reached Jakarta the next day.
Three weeks later, Yokowi gave an emotional speech in Jayapura expressing his condolences to the families of the victims and promised that the violence in Papua would be addressed.
"I want the case investigated immediately so that never happens again."
Security Minister Wiranto said in October 2016 that he would launch human rights violations outside the legal system.
However, he immediately began to withdraw his speeches.
"Most of the violations occurred a long time ago,
1990s and early 2000s.
The most important thing is that we have decided to investigate the violations, but certain processes are needed for it," he said.
In an interview with TIME magazine in Jakarta on 5 June 2017, Wiranto had already changed his mind. He said he was not going to start surveys in Papua.
"Everything will be settled in court," he said.
The UN accuses Wiranto of "crimes against humanity". The crimes are related to the deaths of more than 1,000 people in the bloody independence vote in East Timor in 1999. Wiranto told TIME magazine that 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua have already been investigated, including the events in Paniai.
The families of the Paniai victims are in a dark disbelief about the claims.
"I have been interviewed four times in the last three years, but things have not progressed in any way," Yohanes says.
"I'm tired of this already."
He says he still lives in fear, even though it has been years since the event.
"I am afraid," he says.
"I'm afraid the army will arrest me, and I'm afraid I'll be shot."
His brother Yacobus confirms that the Pania people are afraid to discuss the event.
He says the soldiers had assaulted him after he helped bury four of the victims.
"The soldiers will find me after the victims are buried," he says.
The shootings are not over.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police shot villagers in the neighboring Paniai area of Deiyai.
One was killed and 17 injured in a conflict between the villagers and the head of the construction company, which originated when the manager refused to take the man who had lost consciousness to the hospital.
The man who needed hospitalization was 24-year-old Ravianus Douw, who had been caught in the water while fishing on a nearby river, who died on his way to the hospital.
The angry villagers demonstrated at the construction site in front of the company's office.
Police said the villagers stoned police officers who responded with warning shots.
However, locals say that the mobile police unit of the Indonesian paramilitary police opened fire on the crowd, killing one of the villagers.
"We are terrified. We fear revenge," says 29-year-old Dominggu Badii, who lives near the hospital and saw the wounded brought to treatment.
"I've been hiding at home for two days."
The Deiyai parliament has called for the police officers who fired the shots to be held accountable and for the mobile police unit to be withdrawn from the area.
Paniai has always been a problem for the Indonesian government.
The lack of real development feeds dissatisfaction in the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribes, which live in the lush central highlands of Papua.
Many have joined the Papua Liberation Movement (OPM), an army of rebels who claim to defend the rights of parrots through occasional attacks and kidnapping of Indonesian army soldiers.
Some of the OPM leaders are from Paniai, such as Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
The army has responded to the rebellion by arbitrarily arresting and imprisoning thousands of people in Pania in the name of "security of national sovereignty".
Some of the detainees will never come back.
Among the Papuans, Paniai is known as a "sad, forgotten place".
Poverty feeds dissatisfaction.
There is little rice for sale in Enarotal, and that too is too expensive for locals,
As well as bread.
People grow their food themselves: mainly sweet potatoes and some fruit and leafy vegetables.
Cultivation is the work of women, and one woman may be responsible for four or five sweet potato fields.
Most of the harvest is for the family, and the rest is sold in the market.
Ten sweet potatoes cost only 10,000 rupees (75 cents).
Over time, differences in the livelihoods of locals and migrants have increased, and the number of migrants has increased since new routes were opened at Nabire Airport.
There are few jobs and they usually go to better educated and wealthier migrants than locals.
Few parrots have enough capital and expertise to run their own business competitively.
"Young people don't want to stay in the village because there's no work or money here," says John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai Tribal Council.
The remote Papua is overlooked in the world.
In addition, restrictions on international news coverage remain strict.
Earlier this year, French journalists Franck Escudie and Basille Longchamp were deported from Papua, despite being granted a rare filming permit. The official reason was their inability to cooperate with local institutions.
According to Phelim Kine, Deputy Director of Human Rights Watch Asia, Jokowi has not kept his election promises, and has not increased transparency or promoted development by removing restrictions on news coverage.
"The journalists reporting on the troubled easternmost provinces of Papua and Western Papua face new risks: refusing a visa and blacklisting," Kine said in a statement.
The lack of freedom of the press means that the Indonesian government is only pressured by Papua's immediate neighbours.
In March, six Pacific states — Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, Marshall Islands, and Solomon Islands — urged the UN Human Rights Council to investigate the "numerous and widespread violations" of Papua, including the Paniai shooting.
These states have also traditionally supported the Papua Liberation Movement.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arrmanatha Nasir denied the allegations and told reporters in Jakarta that "Indonesia is still a democracy with freedom of the press, so it would be difficult to cover up evidence of human rights violations."
Locals want foreign governments to intervene.
When a Dutch official delegation led by human rights ambassador Kees Van Bar visited Jayapura on 4 May 2017, the locals broke the silence and expressed their desire for freedom, a source who remained anonymous at the meeting says.
Indonesia has a 2019 presidential election, but the parrots say they are no longer likely to vote for Yokowi.
"Jokowi means well, but there are people around him who are involved in the Paniai shooting," says Gobai, chairman of the tribal council.
He wants Jokowi to know the situation of the Paniais: they live under the rule of a greedy and unpredictable army in want and poverty, virtually without health care services and educational opportunities.
Gobai says that the Paniais, like the other parrots, consider the votes they cast to Yokowi to be a "debt" that must be repaid.
"They don't want money, they just want justice," he says.
Despite the threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the Paniai shooting once again symbolically demonstrated resistance: they buried one of the victims in the country across the police station and military office.
They know they may never get justice, but at least they won't let those responsible forget their crimes.
"My family member was killed," Yacobus says with his head down.
"What else can we do?"
