Georgia massacre: Activists re-raised racist lynching in hope of justice
A Ford Mercury-branded car passes a crowd in Monroe's small town in the Georgian countryside and continues its journey towards the small Moore's Ford Bridge.
The car has four black passengers and a white driver, four armed men blocking the road before the car reaches the bridge.
The leader of the crowd, a middle-aged man in a striped suit, takes a deep breath from his cigar and picks through the windshield.
The passengers are scared.
"Roger, n--u!" the man coughs.
"Get out of the car!"
The screams break the silence when a young black man is pulled out of the front seat.
Fortunately, this shocking event is just a re-slap that aired on 22 July 2017.
However, the sighs of shock are genuine when the noose is threaded into the neck of "Roger".
Since 2005, human rights organizations have returned to Moore's Ford Bridge to reshape the 1946 events, when the Ku Klux Klan lynched two black couples, Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and Mae Murray Dorsey.
No one has been charged with the murders.
"It's confusing that no one has been arrested over the years — even though murderers live among us and many need to know who they are," says Tyrone Brooks, who helps with the arrangements for the re-raft.
"It is a disgrace to history, but above all it is a burden that weighs on our soul."
Brooks is a 71-year-old civil rights activist and former Georgian congressman.
For him, re-slapping is a startling call to action, and it also reminds Monroe residents that injustice has never been corrected.
"We want those responsible to be tried, and we want things to be finally closed, and we want to recover from grief and make peace, but above all, we want justice," Brooks says.
"We can't recover and make peace until we get justice."
The coroner covers the body of a victim who died in the Georgian massacre on 27 July 1946.
According to FBI documents received by NBC news, more than 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties were suspected of lynching.
No one was charged with murder.
Although the culprits have been free for decades, activists say the motives for lynching have been known to locals all along: politics and sex.
In 1946, black people in the state of Georgia were allowed to vote for the first time in presidential elections by a Supreme Court decision in April, and elections were held in the summer.
The FBI said there was an incident at the time of the election where black tenant farmer Roger Malcom stabbed white landowner Barnett Hester in a fight that apparently involved Malcom's wife Dorothy.
Brooks said the city rumored that Hester had had an affair with Dorothy and that Dorothy was expecting her child.
According to FBI reports, on July 25, 1946, the influential white landowner Loy Harrison paid Malcom's $600 bail against which he was released from prison.
On the way home, Malcom and Dorothy were accompanied by their cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey.
The crowd stopped their cars before Moore's Ford Bridge.
"It turns out Harrison ordered and orchestrated the murders," the FBI report said.
"It is also evident that there was a conspiracy between the state and local authorities, and the authorities were involved in the murders and destroyed the evidence and did not reveal the identity of the witnesses."
Brooks puts it more succinctly.
"It was a suffrage murder," he says.
"They were murdered because they wanted to signal to black people that the same thing would happen to them if they were going to vote."
Cassandra Greene has been directing the re-emergence of the Georgian massacre for almost a decade.
The motion is extremely realistic and captivating, a description of shocking racism that many would like to believe has already disappeared from today's United States.
It's hard to watch the show, but even harder not to look at what Greene says is meant to be.
"We don't want to talk about lynching because we'd have to face our own dark sides," the director says.
"But I can't establish a relationship with you if you can't hear me or you don't want to hear what I've been through."
On the first day, about 30 actors — a dozen black and twenty white — gathered to listen to Greene's routine summary of the performance.
Wade Marbaugh is Greene's assistant director.
He has been playing the local Ku Klux Klan leader for years, but the role is always as difficult and repulsive.
"I feel dirty because I'm not myself," Marbaugh says.
"However, it is important that this aspect of history is also kept on display so that it will never happen again."
On the other side of the room, Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, or Roger Malcom and Barnett Hester, practice their lines.
The show begins with Malcom screaming and pushing Hester, and he's furious that Hester has had an affair with Dorothy.
"Didn't you hear? I said leave my lands, n--u!"
Rascona, or Hester, responds.
Then the punch goes.
And then everyone (at least all black actors) bursts into laughter.
Greene laughs the hardest.
"What?!" Rascona asks.
He's confused.
"Did I accidentally hit too hard?" he asks.
"No," Greene throws.
"I just don't think white people used the word n--u at the time."
"Yes," another black actor confirms.
"It's slang, you have to use a longer version."
The subject of the performance is unpleasant, but the room is dominated by a friend spirit.
Everyone wants to succeed, and not just for the performance, and they want to honor the memory of those killed.
The scene starts over.
Now Rascona's words are sneering.
Nobody laughs.
The re-slapping ends quickly and violently.
Screaming, shots — and silence.
A woman dressed in a black funeral costume stands by the bodies and sings Billie Holiday's Strange Fruit.
His voice is broken in every other word.
A few tens of meters away, fifty spectators wipe sweat and tears from their eyes.
Almost exactly half of the audience are black and half are white.
Among them is a couple who have come to see a show from Ithaca, New York, but most are local.
They have been under Brooks' guidance at the victims' graves in Georgia's oppressive humidity.
The murders have changed from a story to a reality, and the atmosphere at the scene is heavy.
After the song performance, Greene invites the crowd to inspect the bodies.
Children squat to look at artificial blood and motionless bodies and whisper to each other.
"They're not really dead," the little boy mutters like to remind himself.
In a few minutes, Greene will thank the audience.
Actors who play lynchers take off their cloaks and wipe tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbaugh, a man who played the local Ku Klux Klan leader.
Nick Rascona hugs two actors and then bursts into tears after a tough performance.
"Don't worry," the woman in the show comforts.
"We know you're not him.
You did this for a good reason."
Later, the audience and actors gather for a dinner together.
The white couple from Altanta are busy discussing the performance with the black couple they just met.
Denise Duplinski finds it difficult to find words when describing the feelings evoked by the performance.
"It's hard to listen to horrible words and watch the horrible things that people say and do that look like you — just because they look like you," he says.
"I was made to find that lynchings are still happening," he added. "They're just called arrests."
On the other side of the room, Brooks recalls the development of civil rights for listeners sitting at the same table.
He says he has already started planning next year's performance.
"Re-launch is a powerful experience because it describes the horrors we experience, but it's also an educational experience," Brooks says.
"The message is that this can happen again if we don't learn from it.
Those who do not know their history are doomed to repeat it."
