New results of Swedish asylum seekers' age tests announced
The latest results of medical age tests for asylum seekers in Sweden have been announced. The results of the tests carried out using the new assessment method reveal that more than 80% of those tested were determined to be over 18 years of age, but not everyone considers the tests to be reliable.
The Swedish National Forensic Agency began testing earlier this year.
The tests can be used to assess the age of the asylum seeker more accurately than before, and a new test was introduced after the Swedish Immigration Service was criticised for failing to determine the actual age of applicants who claimed to be minors.
The Finnish Immigration Service has commissioned 6,880 tests to date, and the forensics agency has now announced the results of 2,481 tests. The tests were conducted between mid-March and the end of July 2017.
80% of the tested, or 2002 asylum seeker, were determined to be over 18 years of age, and in 25 cases the forensic agency determined that the test was "possibly 18 years of age or older".
432 cases concluded that the asylum seeker is "possibly under 18 years of age".
Tests were only conducted in cases where there was reason to doubt the age indicated by the applicant.
Johan Göransson of the Forensics Agency says that the results are consistent with those of previous months.
"The figures are quite consistent. There are no major differences in statistics from previous months," he told The Local.
Although a large number of applicants were determined to be over 18 years of age, this does not necessarily mean that applicants have lied about their age.
In May, the agency announced the results of 581 tests and announced that there were "references in 442 cases that the subject is 18 years of age or older".
When Svenska Dagbladet examined the same results, it became apparent that in 243 cases the applicant had openly stated that he would be 18 this year.
The medical age assessment method used in the tests takes X-rays of wisdom teeth and magnetic images of knee joints. Then the images are analyzed by dentists and radiologists. The method has also been criticized.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus, an endocrinologist at the Karolinska Institutet, whose work involves assessing the biological maturity of humans. The assessment can be used to determine whether a person has had puberty earlier or later than usual.
"I have had reason to think about it, and I think the method used is not the right one.
Determining biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we can't determine age for sure, we shouldn't pretend we can do it," he told the Metro newspaper.
However, Göransson, the forensic agency, defended the accuracy of the tests: "In general, one can say that the risk of determining a child as an adult is low.
The risk is highest in a situation where the test will soon be 18 years old, with a risk of about 10%."
