How the financial rules of football affect Neymar's transfer to Paris
The provisions restricting the spending of European football clubs do not prevent Neymar from being transferred from Barcelona, Spain to Paris Saint-Germain, France, the most expensive player transfer ever made.
Its possible consequences for Paris Saint-Germain (PSG) are decided by UEFA, which regulates European football, and can prevent teams from participating in the prestigious Champions League.
UEFA introduced fair play financial rules in 2011, which require PSG to be able to demonstrate that Neymar's transfer has been funded without major losses.
Barcelona was paid 222 million euros to terminate the Brazilian contract, and Neymar's annual salary for the new club moves in tens of millions of dollars.
There are many economic aspects to Neymar's transfer to France.
PSG has no trouble paying Neymar's transfer amount and connecting him to its star guard, as the club is funded by a dynasty rich in Qatar's oil.
Clubs are allowed to spend large sums on acquiring players, but they must be balanced with real sources of income so that the football-related business is not loss-making.
The financial rules for fair play were drawn up on the initiative of Michel Platinum, a Frenchman elected as UEFA president in 2007.
As a former footballer, Platini felt that the pursuit of success by debt was cheating and led to serious problems if banks or owners withdrew their support.
In 2011, the focus of fair play financial rules shifted from clubs' debts to monitoring their losses.
The change meant that the first implementation of Roman Abramovich's business model used by Chelsea in 2003 became significantly more difficult. Abramovich bought a promising team, spent huge sums of money on player acquisitions and created a global brand.
