As of September, patients may be prescribed a "reverse" anti-HIV drug. The Supreme Court concluded a dispute over the funding of the drug in the English Public Health System (NHS).
NHS reported that pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is prescribed to approximately 10,000 people during the first three-year trial. A pre-interference drug has been found to reduce the risk of infection by about 86% in individuals at high risk.
The NHS agreed to fund the experiment after the Court of Appeal upheld the Supreme Court's ruling last year, which states that the NHS is able to pay for PrEP, although claims that local authorities should fund it.
Simon Stevens, the head of the English NHS, called the decision announced on Thursday a "significant new intervention", and was described by the National AIDS Organization as "decisive for an important moment."
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield are the first to begin taking registrations for an experiment that will expand to other clinics in October. The experiment will reach its full scope in England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV medicine taken before sexual intercourse that reduces the risk of infection.
Experiments have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV infections in risk groups.
A drug taken before sexual intercourse means that there are enough drugs in the body during intercourse that prevent HIV infection.
The drug can be taken daily or two hours before sex.
The target group for treatment includes gay men, bisexual men and transgender people, as well as people with HIV-positive partners who do not receive effective treatment.
Clinics select eligible applicants for the experiment from men, women and transgender people, as well as those whose HIV-positive partner is not known to receive antiretroviral treatment for their disease.
People living in England and enrolled in general medical care can also apply for an experiment at their local sexual health clinic.
The program costs £10 million, and the English NHS signed a contract for medicines this week after an international tender.
The purpose of the experiment is to assess the potential of PrEP by collecting extensive clinical evidence of its targeting, taking and implementation.
"This significant new intervention should complement and enhance the already existing diverse and increasingly effective means of preventing HIV," says Stevens.
"That again one remarkable achievement in the struggle that has been going on for over 30 years to solve one of humanity's greatest health challenges."
"This is a crucial moment in the fight against HIV," said Deborah Gold, director of the National AIDS Organization.
"If PrEP is properly targeted at those in need and at risk, it can have a revolutionary effect on the HIV epidemic in England.
As of September, those at risk will receive a drug through an NHS-funded experiment, the use of which they can decide independently without the need to negotiate with a partner. It will have an empowering effect that will improve the lives of a great many people.
This was welcome news."
"Now the most important thing is to ensure that the experiment is launched quickly throughout the country and no one at risk is excluded from it," says Ian Green, Director of the Terrence Higgins Foundation.
"The PrEP drug used in the experiment has been acquired, and we will soon be able to protect ten thousand people at risk from HIV infection."
"The start of the PREP experiment is a welcome event that was protracted in vain for several months due to the government's slow-motion," said Sharon Hodgson, the shadow government's health minister.
"We have evidence that the drug can have a revolutionary effect on our work we do to prevent HIV and stop the spread of this threatening disease.
The experiment will help us to better understand the real benefits of PrEP.
