"This is incredible," Ferrell thought.
But death was nothing new to him and his community.
He put his phone away, and when he returned to Twitter later that night, it was reported that people were gathering on Canfield Drive.
Users posted pictures of police lock tapes and screaming people, as well as a man who claimed to be Brown's father, whose sign said, "Ferguson police just killed my unarmed son!"
Ferrell followed a real-time video footage of police standing in front of protesters with a barking dog.
He also says he saw a video of another police officer tuning his rifle and shouting, "I'll kill all of you... animals."
"This is not normal," Ferrell remembers.
"It wasn't the kind of murder we're already used to and could be called typical.
That's when I felt cold colors.
I was angry and crying."
He booked a return flight home the next day.
The plane landed at 11 p.m. Ferrell went to pick up his six-year-old daughter at his father's house and decided they would leave for Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson in the next nearly three years has been the subject of the documentary "Whose Streets?", which premiered in cinemas on August 11, 2017.
The film is a story of survival and protest, love and loss, and strength and perseverance from the perspective of the local people who took to the streets to demand answers.
As Ferrell drove towards Ferguson with his daughter dressed in a flower dress and a crown compatible with it, they had a re-conversation about "what it's like to live black and under what circumstances." They had talked about it countless times before that morning.
"Remember when I told you how black people have had to fight for the things they believe in?" Ferrell remembers saying to his daughter.
"We're going to Ferguson because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and it's not right."
"I couldn't help but take my daughter with me," Ferrell later told me.
"The events of today are... the culmination of events of the past.
My daughter has a right to know it and grow up to it.
He must be equipped for activism and organization, but he must also know the different layers and conditions of the experience of living black. And he must know what we need to do to free ourselves.
Fortunately, although I have been able to protect her from blatant racism, she is still like other black girls.
I feel like I would hurt him if I protected him from reality."
Their first stop in Ferguson was South Florissant Road, located opposite the police station, which became a campground for activists as they waited for information on the case and eventually learned that no charges would be filed against the police.
From there, Ferrell and his daughter went to help a local entrepreneur who made lunch packages.
They packed lunches in bags and distributed them to protesters.
Ferrell gradually began to view activism in a new way.
"My activism changed completely after August 9," he says. While studying at the University of Missouri in St. Louis, Ferrell was the president of an organization of minority nursing students. At that time, he focused on food law and health inequalities in black communities.
"I had no experience in organizing.
Somehow it just happened."
Weeks later, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, the documentary's assistant director, in the evening demonstration.
Folayan said that he and photographer Lucas Alvarado-Farrar "wanted to simply tell what was happening.
Ferrell was reminded of a doubt, and he asked, "Do you really want to tell me what's happening, or do you want a story you can use?"
The suspicion was based on the countless times that people, usually whites, had appeared in the local community, who just wanted to benefit from its difficulties and perseverance.
"We had heard that those born and raised in Ferguson had no voice in common," Folayan recently said in an interview. "We wanted to do things differently."
Folayan had already contacted Assistant Director Damon Davis, known for his activism among prisoners sentenced to death.
Davis' involvement led Ferrell to join the project along with six other locals, following the events of Brown's shooting in the years that followed.
"This is not a documentary where someone speaks to us or speaks for us, we speak," Davis says.
"For me, the most important thing was how local people are portrayed in the movie because I'm portrayed the same way."
Folayan said the intention was not to focus on Ferrell's experiences, because they wanted to show that the popular movement "is not about a charismatic leader but a community". However, Ferrell proved to be the most open to the people being described.
That's why the documentary features surprisingly private aspects of Ferrell's life, such as falling in love and getting married.
"I felt pretty naked," Ferrell laughs as he tells me what it felt like to see the movie for the first time.
"But I understood that this work and the human description of blacks require a certain vulnerability."
In addition, Ferrell's story times and refocuses the role of black queer women in the wider Black Lives Matter movement.
The movement was born on social media (#BlackLivesMatter) after police shot black teenage boy Trayvon Martin in 2012. Two of the movement's three founders identify with queer identity.
"The leadership of black queer women has kept the whole movement going," Ferrell says. "It's because we have to fight all the time on many fronts.
Black queer women have had to endure everything."
Folayan agrees, "The movement is indeed maintained by black women, among whom there are many queer women."
However, he stresses that Ferrell was not selected for the documentary "self-intentionally" because of his queer identity.
"He got the energy moving," Folayan says.
"It's no coincidence, however, that he was on the front line. Black queer women live at the intersection of many things, and they have a lot at stake.
His energy is transmitted from the screen."
The news crews have left Ferguson long ago, but the relationship between the community and the police is still strained.
Ferrell still has two and a half years of parole left, and he was convicted of blocking the freeway at the demonstration.
His description of the social policy climate of his home corners is short and concise: "Mixed."
Yet he still relies on the slogan he memorized on the streets of Ferguson three years ago:
"Our duty is to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We must love and support each other.
We can only lose our chains."
