The Origin of a Comic Book: The Story of a Castle
The small Scotney Castle in County Kent is now known for its Squeeze music video and Margaret Thatcher's hideout from the 1970s and 1980s.
However, it has 700 years of turbulent history behind it. Now this castle, located in a charming location in the Bewl River Valley, is the subject of a comic book written by Jamie Rhodes, a mop-haired writer fond of old documents.
"I think it's great to be able to study a text written by a person who died over 300 years ago," Rhodes says longingly.
"I feel a personal connection when I hold a letter in my hand."
Rhodes' book, A Castle in England, tells the stories of families living in Scotney from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian period. Each story was illustrated by a different artist, promising British cartoonist: Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer or Isabel Greenberg.
This is not Rhodes' first archive-based book. In 2014, he published Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories, inspired by documents from the National Library of Britain. The project was emotional.
"I moved to tears when I noticed a thumbprint in the letter, written by a double agent working for the Jacobites in the 18th century," Rhodes says.
"It was his fingerprint!
And the letters smell like smoke, because at that time fire was used as lighting.
Three centuries later, the smell makes the reader feel that he is on the spot himself.
I love archives!"
A writer attracted to old documents was allowed to live in the castle for almost four months with the support of the National Trust Foundation and the National Art Council of England, which felt too good to be true. He admits that he could not stay in the castle without delay for a little longer than he would have hoped.
He spent the days studying Victorian "new" castle, archives, treasures, and rarities, such as hyena heads hung on walls and bottles that were moated for centuries.
He toured the ruins and estates of the old castle and talked with forest rangers, gardeners and sometimes artists who also illustrated the book.
In the evenings, he "took whiskey and started writing".
Scotney's closer history is quite unknown, as the castle was not transferred entirely to the National Trust Foundation until the death of the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey, in 2006.
When Rhodes arrived about ten years later, the Foundation staff was just starting to go through the archive. Rhodes describes that the archives had been kept for hundreds of years using the same method: taking everything extra to the attic.
The archives contained diaries, letters from the days of the English Empire, and maps of who owned what. "You could imagine that land disputes are boring," Rhodes says. "However, here families even fought for one birch.
I thought we should let it go."
Some of the stories in the book advance from the castle to English history, such as The Labourer, which is about a man who joins the English peasant revolt shortly after the castle was completed in 1381.
"Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex mentions that there was a riot in the castle in 1380," Rhodes says.
"The peasant revolt in England began in the same area, and it occurred to me that the rebellion could begin with a riot.
Maybe these events are connected?"
Other stories in the book are closely related to the history of the castle — such as The Priest, a story about a priest hidden by the Darrell family for seven years during the English Reformation.
The Smuggler, on the other hand, tells the story of smuggler Arthur Darrell from the 18th century. He is said to have staged his own funerals with the stones of a coffin (it was discovered years later when his tomb was opened).
The Darrells are Rhodes' favorite family in Scotney. "The family men seem to have been quite a little bit of a rascal, and they were constantly in debt and bought things they couldn't afford.
The men in the Darrell family solved their debt problems by marrying wealthy old women, and I see them as handsome guys who knew how to court heiress."
Now Rhodes is looking for new writing experiences.
He spent two weeks in Finland writing a comic book about Life Hill, a sanatorium that operated in the early 20th century, of which only a eutrophic plot remains.
Scotney Castle has a special place in his heart.
"It was sad to leave there," he says.
"I didn't want to go back to this damn everyday life yet."
