Red meat, dairy products and chocolate may relieve irritable bowel syndrome
Red meat and chocolate may sound like nightmares in the digestive system.
However, a recent study claims the opposite: a diet rich in meat protein and dairy products may ease irritable bowel syndrome.
Irritable bowel syndrome is an incurable disease that affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 people in the UK. It causes stomach cramps, swelling, recurrent or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
People with irritable bowel syndrome are usually advised to avoid meat and dairy products. However, researchers at Washington University found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in protein helps the body develop immune cells that strengthen bowel tolerance.
According to Marco Colonna, director of the study, immune cells guard the swamp and ensure that harmful microbes do not enter the body in food.
The cells that balance the cells that cause inflammation, which strengthen tolerance, protect the body without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance drops too close to inflammation, irritable bowel syndrome may result.
Experiments found that immune cells that strengthen tolerance are found in mice with a specific bacterium in their intestines.
This bacterium needs tryptophan to start showing up immune cells. Tryptophan is one of the building blocks of proteins.
"We found a link between Lactobacillus reuteri and the development of tolerance-promoting cells. Lactobacillus reuteri is part of the normal microbiome of the intestine," Professor Colonna says.
"The more tryptophan there was in the diet of mice, the more such immune cells they had."
If the same works in humans, a combination of Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria and a diet rich in tryptophan can strengthen intestinal tolerance and reduce inflammatory sensitivity.
While studying tolerance-enhancing immune cells, postdoctoral researcher Luisa Cervantes-Barragan found that although one group of mice had such cells, they did not exist in mice of the same mouse species that were kept separate from the other group.
He suspected that the difference was related to microbiomes in the intestines of mice, i.e. the normal community of bacteria, fungi and viruses in the digestive tract.
When the intestinal DNA of mice was examined, six species of bacteria were observed, which were found in mice with immune cells but not in other mice.
When Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria were administered to mice grown in a sterile environment that did not have a intestinal microbiome and did not develop immune cells, immune cells began to appear.
The researchers wanted to find out how bacteria affect the immune system, growing Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in the liquid and transferring small amounts of fluid — without bacteria — to immature immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells evolved into tolerance-enhancing cells.
When the active ingredient was purified from the liquid, it proved to be a byproduct of tryptophan metabolism known as indole-3 lactic acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in mouse nutrition, the number of tolerance-enhancing cells increased by about 50 percent. When the amount of tryptophan was halved, the number of cells fell by half from the previous one.
Cervantes-Barragan says that humans have the same tolerance-enhancing cells as mice, and most of us have Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in our digestive tract.
It is not yet known whether tryptophan byproducts from Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria cause cells to develop in humans in the same way as in mice. However, genetic defects associated with tryptophan have been observed in people with irritable bowel syndrome.
"We probably want to promote the development of such cells because they regulate inflammation on the inner surfaces of the intestines," Cervantes-Barragan says.
"High tryptophan levels combined with Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria may contribute to their generalization."
