White House exhibit cost thousands of dollars to taxpayers
The White House's decision last month to fly a naval helicopter to the White House's southern grass field for an event presenting American production cost taxpayers $24,000, as evidenced by military documents received by TIME magazine.
The green-and-white Sikorsky VH-3D helicopter is referred to as Marine One when the president is on board it, a attraction to an event held at the White House on 17 July 2017 that featured American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and a group of White House officials became acquainted with the products from all 50 states.
In addition to a helicopter manufactured in Connecticut, a sailboat from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a forklift from Mississippi were on display.
The White House military office had requested a helicopter on site by task-specific order just about 36 hours before it landed on the southern grass field for an "exceptional" event, as shown in the documents of the Navy HMX-1 helicopter squadron.
"I just wanted to make sure you were aware of this because it's an exceptional event that gets a lot of visibility," the commander of the HMX-1 unit wrote in an email the day before the event to his supervisor, who is an assistant commandant for naval airlift.
The message said that the helicopter would arrive at the southern grass field on 17 July at 7 a.m. and the event would start at 3 p.m. The helicopter would not leave the scene until after the grass field was emptied between 6 and 9 in the evening.
The message also mentioned that if the helicopter were delayed from the White House, another crew would be needed due to restrictions on service times.
The original crew was in a helicopter during the event, and the unit's security personnel were at the helicopter's house while it was on the ground.
It is not clear from the documents received by TIME magazine whether another crew was eventually needed.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal workers from using state property for political purposes.
According to the documents, HMX-1 asked if the event was a violation of the law.
"One of our questions was whether this was a violation of the Hatch Act, and we were told not to break," the commander wrote.
"It sounds like you can participate," the assistant commandant replied.
Made in America was the official White House event, so it was not covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political tones.
At the event, the president spoke out in favour of the health care reform that was being discussed at the time in the Senate and looser state regulation.
Using a Marine One helicopter and an Air Force One for political purposes is not a new phenomenon.
Presidents must use them on their travels,
But using them only for photos is unusual.
Trump's actions attracted attention in February when Air Force One rolled the background to the presidential campaign event in Melbourne, Florida. Trump has strongly criticized the use of his predecessor's presidential aircraft on Twitter.
"The White House is very pleased with Made in America, which showcased products made by American workers from American materials from all 50 states," said White House Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 unit crews regularly conduct training flights in the Washington area and train on the southern grass field to bring the president to the White House with centimetres of accuracy.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 made 58 training landings at the White House.
According to one official, flights to Made in America were part of the crew's monthly training quota.
The unit's helicopters also flew 11 hours in "non-presidential support missions" that day.
The White House said no other costs were incurred by taxpayers.
A spokesman for Sikorsky said the company was not involved in organizing a helicopter demonstration on the White House's southern grass field.
HMX-1 has no records of flights related to the President's duties, and it is difficult to accurately estimate the costs of the event.
According to the Ministry of Defence's 2017 hourly compensation, the VH-3D helicopter has a compensation level of $24,380 per flight hour.
According to HMX-1 unit documents, flights from Quantico Base in Virginia to the White House and back lasted a total of an hour.
The White House says the helicopter's operating costs are clearly lower.
"The calculation of the cost to taxpayers according to the level of compensation is misleading," Walters says.
"The estimated level of compensation includes personnel, maintenance and many other so-called embedded costs, which are taken into account in the annual appropriations."
According to a 2015 survey by RAND, compensation levels do not include personnel costs, but take into account fuel, maintenance and contract costs.
At the time of the event, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of a helicopter at the event.
"The idea is to introduce American production," Spicer said.
"I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud to be involved in ensuring national security and thereby employing probably hundreds or thousands of people.
And I think, like most Americans, we are proud of the helicopter and other defense equipment that many Americans have worked hard for.
It is entirely appropriate to bring it up."
It is not certain if Trump was in a helicopter during the event, but at least he sat down with the driver of the fire truck.
